 {"id":"bd-1w9","title":"demo_showcase UI: command palette overlay (Ctrl+P)","description":"# demo_showcase UI — Command Palette Overlay (Ctrl+P)

## Purpose

A modern-feeling command palette is one of the most “real app” UI elements we can ship, and it’s a perfect vehicle to show:

- scissor clipping (scrolling results list)
- alpha blending (glass overlay)
- hit testing (click commands)
- text styling (match highlights)

## Behaviors

- Open/close: Ctrl+P toggles.
- Typing edits the query buffer.
- Up/Down selects a command.
- Enter executes the selected command.
- Esc closes.

Mouse support:
- scroll wheel scrolls results
- click selects + executes

## Command Set (Minimum)

Commands should map to real demo actions:

- Toggle Help (F1)
- Start Tour (Ctrl+T) / Stop Tour
- Switch UI Theme: Synthwave Dark / Paper Light / Solarized / High Contrast
- Switch Highlight Theme (mirrors UI theme mapping)
- Toggle Debug Overlay
- Force Full Redraw
- Toggle Threaded Renderer (optional / gated)
- Navigate: Overview / Editor / Preview / Logs / Unicode / Performance

No fuzzy matcher dependency; start with deterministic substring scoring.

## Rendering Notes

- Use the overlay system bead for backdrop + panel body.
- Results list must be clipped to its viewport via scissor.
- Selected row uses a strong accent + subtle alpha fill.
- Query input row should show a blinking caret (time-driven) even if we don’t use the terminal cursor.

## Integration

- Executing a command produces:
  - a toast (see toast bead)
  - a log entry (logs panel)
  - state changes (mode/theme/panel)

